++ A word of warning
The Triliminal Gates are only found within the deepest depths of the --Dardic-- Labyrinths, guarded by their most ancient --Sorcerers-- and most dangerous minions. Only the greatest of our heroes should even risk delving so deep into the subterrene. Should you attempt such an expedition, trust in your steel, skill, and courage, but do not let your courage become foolhardiness. **Our Lady** has few enough heroes sworn to her cause, and an ignominious retreat is preferable to a futile death.

The dangers of the Labyrinths are five-fold.
* First, the twisting of time and locus: in the labyrinths, one will find that a plumb line does not point towards the earth, that four right corners will not form a square, that a chamber an ell wide without will be a league wide within, and a thousand years may be as a day.
* Second, the infernal devices within. The --Dardics-- fill their labyrinths with all manner of snares, traps, and mechanisms to slay those who would trespass within them.
* Third, the beasts and minions that guard the Labyrinths. These range from unfortunate souls lost within, slave-soldiers forced to guard the chambers, and monstrous beasts formed by --Dardic-- sorcery.
* Fourth, the eyes and ears of the --Dardic-- sorcerers perceive all that occurs within the Labyrinths they have created. Stealth and magic may conceal you for a time, but should the Sorcerer become aware of your intrusion, they will take notice and your task will become harder.
* Fifth: the allure of wealth, glory, and gain. The Labyrinths contain many treasures and wonders that will serve desires crass and noble, can fund causes both sinister and benevolent. Many delves have failed due to distraction from the discovery of a previously unknown treasure. Keep to the narrow path, and do not let yourself become distracted by vanities.

Experience and practice have shown us that five are the best number for those who would delve into a Labyrinth. It is recommended that this party includes:
* A warrior of great renown, to slay the beasts within.
* A thief of peerless skill, to keep their fellows hidden from the Sorcerers’ eyes.
* A sage wise and cunning, to decipher the mysteries within.
* A chirurgeon well-educated in the healing of wounds and illness.
* A true soul who will guide these other four and keep to the narrow path.

Should you and your companions choose to enter a Labyrinth for the purposes of destroying a Triliminal Gate, keep these principles in mind:

__FIRST__: Prepare yourselves well. Bring weaponry, armor, and magic, but do not neglect sundries such as food, water, reagents, and medicine. Most parties die not to the teeth and fangs of beasts, but to cold, starvation, thirst, and infection.

__SECOND__: You and your companions must be as one. Five strands of rope can withstand great force, a single yarn snaps at the lightest tug. You will be tempted, within the Labyrinth, to divide your numbers: this is the way of folly, for death will claim you one by one in the dark.

__THIRD__: One among you must serve as chronicler and cartographer. This one should be equipped with stylus and tablet, and should keep a map of the Labyrinth as you delve into it, as well as maintaining a record of information obtained during the delve. Should you be forced to retreat, the information you obtain may ensure that subsequent delves are more successful.

__FOURTH__: You must walk a narrow path between haste and indecision. Move too swiftly, and you will fail to perceive traps and threats that will slay you. Move too slowly, and the beasts that dwell within will corner and slay you. The wisest and most experienced among you should be the one to set the pace.

__FIFTH__: When gambling, one must know when to withdraw from the table, and when to remain. Likewise, when you delve into a Labyrinth, you must know when to continue and when to turn back. There comes a time in every delve when one reaches a point of no return, and the only choice that remains is to press on to the conclusion. Pray that when that moment comes, your way home is not blocked to you.

